-- Rupee Weakens to 1-Month Low as Importers Purchase More Dollars
-- B y   J e a n e t t e   R o d r i g u e s
-- 2012-10-29T12:15:59Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-29/rupee-drops-to-1-week-low-on-speculation-importers-buying-dollar.html
India ’s rupee fell to the lowest
level in more than a month on speculation importers stepped up
dollar purchases to pay month-end bills.  Demand for the greenback increased as trading resumed after
a three-day break due to a local holiday, according to Edelweiss
Financial Advisors Ltd. Indian  monetary policy  may have space in
future to support growth if price pressures ease and fiscal and
trade deficits narrow, even as caution is necessary for now to
focus on inflation, the nation’s central bank said in a report
today ahead of its interest-rate decision in Mumbai tomorrow.  The rupee was pressured due to “month-end dollar demand by
 oil companies  and” the long weekend, analysts at Edelweiss
Financial Advisors Ltd., including Mumbai-based Vinay Khattar,
wrote in a report today. “The markets await triggers from the
upcoming RBI monetary policy review.”  The rupee declined 0.9 percent from Oct. 25 to 54.0725 per
dollar in Mumbai, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. It
touched 54.0850 earlier, the lowest level since Sept. 21. One-
month implied volatility, a gauge of exchange-rate swings used
to price options, fell 15 basis points, or 0.15 percentage
point, to 10.10 percent.  The currency could surge in the event of a reduction in the
 Reserve Bank  of India’s benchmark repurchase rate, according to
Edelweiss.  Monetary Policy  The monetary authority will keep the  repurchase rate  at 8
percent tomorrow, according to 16 of 28 economists surveyed by
Bloomberg. Eleven expect a 25 basis point reduction and one
predicts a half-percentage point cut. The central bank will
lower lenders’  reserve requirements  to 4.25 percent from 4.50
percent, according to 18 of the analysts, while eight see no
change and two forecast a cut to 4 percent.  Three-month onshore rupee forwards were at 54.88 per dollar
compared with 54.57 on Oct. 25, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. Offshore non-deliverable contracts were at 54.89
versus 54.50 on Oct. 26. Forwards are agreements to buy or sell
assets at a set price and date. Non-deliverable contracts are
settled in dollars.  To contact the reporter on this story:
